<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>The White Rose CCS project is one of two preferred bidders in the UK Government’s CCS Commercialisation Programme and Europe’s</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Capture Power (CCS37)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; float:left; margin:0pt 9pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:426.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The White Rose CCS project is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">one of two preferred bidders in the UK Government’s CCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Commercialisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and Europe’s only CCS project being considered for EU NER300 funding.</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCS deployment will help to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">minimise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the costs of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decarbonisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCS has the potential to deliver electricity system flexibility, which will be increasingly important with the growth of intermit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tent renewable and inflexible nuclear generation.    </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The technology is proven at pilot scale. The test now is to establish the full CCS chain as a commercial proposition.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">White Rose is a cost effective, realistic and deliverable project, which offers an e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">xcellent opportunity to establish the commercial future of the technology.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK has one of the leading CCS policy and incentives’ frameworks of any European nation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">But it is essential that the Commercialisation Programme delivers on the first two projec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ts in order to establish market confidence. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">That will require a much more collaborative approach from Government in working with the private sector.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The swift introduction of Contracts-for-Difference for CCS will also be key to ensuring CCS becomes commer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">availablein</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the UK.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Significant cost reduction can be achieved by lowering the cost of capital through reducing investment risk and establishing CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">transport &amp; storage infrastructure.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government’s own CCS Roadmap identifies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> clear economic benefits from developing a UK-based CCS industry: between £3-6.5bn nationally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p.a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by the late 2020s.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Creating CCS clusters can help to bring significant benefits and cost reductions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Yorkshire and Humberside region provides an ideal l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocation for a CCS cluster with around 19% of the UK’s CO2 emissions. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A CCS cluster could increase Yorkshire &amp; Humberside’s economic output by 0.8% per year and attract circa £11bn in foreign investment.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The combination of biomass and CCS for power </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">generation even offers the even more exciting prospect of negative emissions.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Detail</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Context: global progress</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Global progress with CCS has been slow compared to estimates by national governments and inter-governmental bodies. Nevertheless, Bloomberg New </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Energy Finance data show that public and private organisations have channelled $26.8bn into CCS commercialisation since 2000. Government grants make up 54% of that total. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Global investment in projects has remained steady since 2009 at around $2.8bn a ye</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ar (BNEF, 7 March 2013). That investment has produced seventeen medium- to-large CCS projects operating, or under construction, with another 55 at the planning stage (GCCSI).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK is one of the leading countries in terms of developing an effective CCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">policy framework, despite slow progress with its attempts to fund demonstration projects (2006-11).  A new approach has emerged in the form of the CCS Commercialisation Programme and the Electricity Market Reform (EMR). This has the potential to match UK C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CS rhetoric and delivery on the ground.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DECC’s Commercialisation Programme has selected two projects – White Rose and Peterhead - to enter negotiations for Front-End Engineering and Design (FEED) studies, with a view to making final investment decisio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns in 2015.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">White Rose is a cost effective, realistic and deliverable project, which offers an excellent opportunity to establish the commercial future of the technology. The project is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Europe’s only CCS project being considered for NER300 funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (for f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urther details on the project see the attached slide pack.) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is essential that the momentum is maintained in the Commercialisation Programme, so that two projects can enter operation in the 2018-2020 timeframe</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As the Committee on Climate Change has said: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘It will be important that the Government continues to learn the lessons of the earlier failed CCS Competition, including the need for rapid progress and avoiding traditional procurement processes unsuited to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a complex first-of-a-kind project.’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(CCC Carbon Budget Progress Report 2013.)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We strongly agree with that view, in particular the need for Government to take a more innovative and collaborative approach, rather than relying on a traditional procurement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">model. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Committee’s questions</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our answers to the Committee’s questions are as follows:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What types of CCS technology are currently being developed and how do they differ from one another?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are currently three main technology options for capturing CO2: pre-combustion, post-combustion and oxy-combustion. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Pre-combustion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is based on gasification, which converts a fossil fuel into synthesis gas composed of CO and hydrogen. CO2 is captured following shift conversion. For power generation, the resulting H2 product is burned in a gas turbine.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Post-combustion capture </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">separat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from the exhaust gases using a solvent.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Oxy-combustion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">burns the fuel in a mixture of oxygen and recycled CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> instead of air. This combustion produces a concentrated stream of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that can be easily separated for subsequent storage. The White Rose</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> project is based on this technology.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Second generation technologies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, such as chemical looping combustion and regenerative calcium cycle are also being looked at because they offer the prospect of future benefits (technology optimization and reduced cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s). </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Two of the partners in the White Rose project - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Alstom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Linde</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (BOC) – have already participated in a number of pilot projects:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Alstom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: projects using oxy-combustion, chilled ammonia, advanced amines or second-generation technologies. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Five units</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have completed tests in the USA &amp; Europe; while </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eight units are in operation or in commissioning.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Linde</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (BOC):</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has built an advanced amines-based pilot plant and an oxy-combustion related pilot plant in Germany and is involved as part of a consortium de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">veloping a potential pre-combustion plant in the USA.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The pilot and validation plants have shown that the technology works. The next step is to establish the commercial credentials of the technology at large-scale with full CCS chain. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">contribution could CCS make towards the UK’s decarbonisation targets? Are the UK Government’s expectations reasonable in this regard?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Power generation accounts for approximately a third of the UK’s CO2 emissions, or 182 million tonnes of CO2 a year (DECC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Capturing and storing that carbon could reduce emissions from fossil fuel power stations by as much as 95%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (ETI, 2013). As the Prime Minister said in a recent Liaison Committee meeting: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decarbonisation targets only really make sense when you </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">know what is going to be possible in terms of carbon capture and storage….</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> If not, you are in quite serious water, because you would be only relying on nuclear and renewable.’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(Liaison Committee, 11 December 2012)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Analysis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by the Government and the Commi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ttee for Climate Change shows that up to 0.6 GW of CCS could be delivered in the UK by 2020; 5-10 GW by 2030 and up to 40 GW by 2050. The CCS Association has argued that 20–30 GW is possible by 2030. The exact number will depend in large part on the succes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s of the current Commercialisation Programme and whether the first two projects, including adequately sized initial CO2 transport and storage infrastructure, can be delivered on time.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With the expected growth of intermittent renewable generation (rising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from 9% of electricity today to 32% by 2030) and the continued contribution of inflexible nuclear generation, it will be important for the UK to maximise the use of flexible, fossil fuel generation. CCS can be designed to enable that flexibility to be real</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ised, whilst ensuring emissions are reduced effectively.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the longer term, CCS combined with biomass is the only low carbon technology that could remove industrial quantities of CO2 from the atmosphere and permanently store it in deep geological for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mations. CO2 is absorbed from the atmosphere during the natural growth process of biomass. Following combustion of the biomass the CO2 is captured and permanently stored providing a net carbon removal from the atmosphere, or ‘negative emissions’. These neg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ative emissions could be used to offset emissions from other harder to decarbonise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sectors. This view was strongly supported by the Committee on Climate Change’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bioenergy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Review (2012). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Are there any potential benefits (e.g. the ability to export CCS t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">echnology abroad) of successfully developing CCS to the UK economy and, if so, what are they?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government’s CCS Roadmap estimated benefits of between £3-6.5 billion a year by the late 2020s to UK-based firms, sustaining between 70,000-100,000 jobs.</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A report by CO2Sense (October 2012) estimated that the development of a CCS cluster in Yorkshire &amp; Humberside could provide a major boost to the UK economy, delivering £1.3bn and 4,000 skilled-jobs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">18.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The report stated that ‘Yorkshire and Humber is the be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">st strategic location in Europe to build a CCS cluster’ and that ‘putting this funding into the region will increase the area’s economic output by 0.8% per year, attract as much as £11billion in foreign investment and a further 11,000 jobs’.  The cluster w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould also have the potential to make a sizeable reduction to the UK’s carbon emissions by transforming one of the UK's highest emitting regions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">19.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Energy Technologies Institute has estimated that the deployment of CCS at scale could cut the UK’s cost o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f meeting climate targets by around 1% of GDP, equivalent to £30–40 billion annually in 2050. (ETI, Mobilising Private Sector Financing report) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">20.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Enhanced hydrocarbon recovery (EHCR) could also deliver benefits to the UK in terms of energy security, balan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce of payments, tax revenues, deferred decommissioning costs and increased employment as well as helping to move CCS down the cost reduction curve.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main barriers (e.g. economic, political, regulatory, scientific and social) to developing lar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ge-scale integrated CCS projects in the UK and internationally? How can they be overcome?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">21.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK has a number of key advantages which make it ideally suited for the deployment of CCS, including:  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Accessible and potentially extensive offshore storage c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">apacity in the North Sea. </span><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:11pt">According to the Energy Technologies Institute, the CO</span><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:11pt">2 </span><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:11pt">storage capacity could be up to ~70 billion </span><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:11pt">tonnes</span><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Existing clusters of power and industrial plants with the potential to share CCS infrastructure. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:11pt">Expertise in the </span><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:11pt">offshore oil and gas industry, which can be transferred to the business of CO</span><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:11pt">2 </span><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:11pt">storage.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:11pt">Academic excellence in CCS research.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">22.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The main barriers in the UK and internationally are economic and political. We agree with much of the analysis in the Governmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t’s CCS Roadmap and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCS Cost Reduction Taskforce report. The CCS Roadmap outlined three broad challenges: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reducing costs and risks to make CCS cost competitive</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Putting in place market frameworks</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Removing key barriers to the deployment of CCS (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e.g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nancial)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">23.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CCS Cost Reduction Taskforce added some further detail in highlighting several key steps:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensure funding mechanisms are fit-for-purpose</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Create bankable contracts</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensure optimal UK CCS transport and storage network configuration</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Incentivise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> CO2 EOR </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Promote characterisation of CO2 storage locations</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Create policy and financing regimes for CCS from industrial CO2</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">24.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that the Commercialisation Programme and the Contracts-for-Difference under EMR should go a long way to addressing the financial and economic challenges for CCS on power generation. Delivery under those mechanisms will require a stable policy fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">amework and a consistent political approach. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is the UK Government’s approach, set out in its CCS Roadmap, likely to incentivise development of CCS in the UK?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">25.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that, with a sensible, co-operative approach to delivering the Commercialisation P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rogramme and the reforms offered through the Electricity Market Review, the UK is well placed to make progress. There is no other country in Europe with such a comprehensive CCS offer: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Arial MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A CCS Commercialisation Programme with £1 billion in capital </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funding.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Feed-in Tariff Contracts-for-Difference.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A £125m R&amp;D programme and a new UK CCS Research Centre.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A clear regulatory framework.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">26.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The key test now is to translate that offer into successful projects on the ground. That will help to prove the techno</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">logy’s commercial credentials and help in keeping up the momentum on cost reduction. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he CCS Cost Reduction Taskforce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report explains how the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">levelised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cost of CCS power generation could fall from around £160/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MWh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for projects with a final investment decisi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on (FID) in 2013, to below £100/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MWh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for FID in 2028. Cost reduction is separated into three broad categories: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improvements in the cost/performance of component technologies (around 25% of the cost reduction); </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increasing the scale/utilisation of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rastructure (50%); and </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reduction in projects’ cost of capital (25%)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We broadly agree with these conclusions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">27.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With 75% of cost reduction coming from lowering the cost of capital and delivering CO2 infrastructure, it is very clear why the current Commer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cialisation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Programme is so important. The Programme is central to convincing investors that cost and risk reductions can be delivered.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">28.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Beyond the first two projects, the Government should set out its approach to supporting further projects to become o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">perational in the early 2020s at the latest. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the consequences of failing to develop CCS and what alternatives are available for decarbonisation if CCS fails?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">29.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the national level, the Energy Technologies Institute has concluded that: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘Without a national CCS infrastructure, the cost of reaching UK Climate Change targets will double from a minimum of around £30bn per year in 2050. This is the equivalent of an additional 2p per kWh on all UK energy use in 2050. Therefore the economic priz</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e of CCS to the UK is potentially considerable. Our calculations show that each five years of delay in implementing CCS until 2030 will add the equivalent of £4bn per annum to the total cost of the compliant UK energy system’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">30.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The 2030 scenarios in DECC’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s Delivery Plan (July 2013) show that if CCS is not commercially available by then, the UK will need greater contributions primarily from nuclear and offshore wind. There has to be question marks over whether those technologies could deliver at the require</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d higher scale, at a reasonable cost to the taxpayer and provide enough generation flexibility.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">31.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Committee’s letter to the Secretary of State (30 November 2011) sums up the position very well:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘…CCS is a vital technology for the low-carbon </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">transition. There would be serious international and economic implications if we were not able to make this technology available. Without it, we may face an impossible trade-off between our environmental objectives and energy security.’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Capture Power</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">32.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The White Rose partners – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Alstom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Drax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and BOC – are planning to build a 426MW oxy-combustion carbon capture and storage (CCS) demonstration project. The project will comprise a state-of-the-art coal-fired power station that will be equippe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d with full CCS technology. It will be built at the existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Drax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> power station site, near Selby, North Yorkshire, and will capture around 90% of emissions. Around two million tonnes of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; vertical-align:-1pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will be transported through the proposed National Grid pipeline fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r permanent undersea storage in the North Sea. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">33.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A slide pack summarising the project is attached. </span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">September 2013</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>